## *-algebra of bounded operators on a Hilbert space

The term "[operator ring](/Operator_ring)" redirects here. It is not to be confused with a [ring operator](/Ring_operator) or [operator assistance](/Operator_assistance), which are entirely different, and frankly, less interesting, concepts.

In the rather unforgiving landscape of [mathematics](/Mathematics), a [von Neumann algebra](/Von_Neumann_algebra), also known as a [W*-algebra](/W*-algebra), is a specific kind of [*-algebra](/Star-algebra). It's not just any collection of [bounded operators](/Bounded_linear_operator) on a [Hilbert space](/Hilbert_space); it must be a fortress, [closed](/Closed_set) against the chaotic tides of the [weak operator topology](/Weak_operator_topology), and it must, without question, contain the [identity operator](/Identity_operator). Think of it as a meticulously constructed, unyielding structure. It's a specialized breed of [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra), which, if you must know, is already a rather rigid construct.

These von Neumann algebras first crawled into existence through the meticulous, and some might say obsessive, studies of [John von Neumann](/John_von_Neumann). His motivations were varied, ranging from the solitary contemplation of [single operators](/Operator_theory) to the grand narratives of [group representations](/Group_representation), the intricate dances of [ergodic theory](/Ergodic_theory), and the unsettling foundations of [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics). His celebrated [double commutant theorem](/Von_Neumann_double_commutant_theorem) is a testament to this, a rather elegant proof that a definition based on the cold logic of [mathematical analysis](/Mathematical_analysis) is, in essence, equivalent to a purely [algebraic](/Abstract_algebra) description – a description of symmetries, no less.

To give you a sense of what we're dealing with, consider two rudimentary examples. They're basic, almost insultingly so, but they serve their purpose:

